# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1876-chicago-white-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The **1876 Boston Red Caps season** was the sixth season of the franchise.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] With the dissolution of the National Association, the Boston team joined the brand new National League.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The team name was changed from the Boston Red Stockings to the **Boston Red Caps** to avoid confusion with the new Cincinnati Red Stockings team.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] Some of the players from the previous year's team defected to other ballclubs, so the team finished further down in the standings this season.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1876 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] It was the team's first season of existence, having been formed as part of the brand new National League in 1876.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] This team was not related (except by name) to the previous Cincinnati Red Stockings National Association team, which had folded in 1870.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] One bright spot for the Reds was the play of Charley Jones, who led the club with a batting average of .286, had the second highest home run total in the league with four, and was among the league leaders in doubles and slugging percentage.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds played their first ever game on April 25, 1876, defeating the St.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Brown Stockings 2–1 at Avenue Grounds.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Wins would be few and far between for the Reds, as after putting up a solid 3–2 record in their opening five games, the Reds would go on an eleven-game losing streak to fall to 3–13.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] After defeating the Hartford Dark Blues 8–2 to end their losing streak, the Reds would then have a thirteen-game losing streak, and saw their record fall to 4–26.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] By the time the season was finished, Cincinnati had the worst record in the National League, as they ended the season with a 9–56 record, 42.5 games behind the first place Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-hartford-dark-blues-season] The **Hartford Dark Blues** joined the new National League for its first season in 1876, and team owner Morgan Bulkeley was the first National League president.
[src:1876-chicago-white-stockings-season/1876-hartford-dark-blues-season] They finished the season in second place.
